CATEGORY_CONTENT["sales-analytics"] = {
 "definition": "provides unified dashboards and reports on rep activity, pipeline velocity, conversion rates, quota attainment, and sales performance, giving leaders the data to manage their teams and forecast results.",
 "definition_expanded": "Sales analytics platforms pull data from your CRM, engagement tools, and revenue systems to create dashboards that answer the questions sales leaders ask every day. Which reps are on pace? Where is pipeline stuck? What is the real conversion rate by stage? How does this quarter compare to last? Most CRMs include basic reporting, but the native dashboards lack the flexibility and depth that data-driven leaders need. Dedicated analytics tools connect multiple data sources, calculate metrics that CRM formulas cannot express, and present them in dashboards designed for sales management rather than IT configuration.",
 "buying_guide": "Before buying a standalone analytics tool, exhaust your CRM's native reporting. Salesforce Reports and Dashboards handle standard metrics, funnel analysis, and activity tracking for many organizations. HubSpot's reporting covers pipeline and rep performance for SMB teams. If native CRM reporting covers 80% of your needs, investing in a better Salesforce dashboard design may deliver more value per dollar than a new tool. Buy dedicated analytics when you need cross-system data (CRM + engagement platform + CS tool), custom metric calculations, or dashboard flexibility your CRM cannot provide.\n\nDefine your analytics audience. Frontline managers need daily activity metrics: calls made, emails sent, meetings booked, opportunities created. VP-level leaders need pipeline velocity, stage conversion, and forecast accuracy. CROs need board-level views: ARR growth, quota attainment by segment, and year-over-year trends. Tools like Atrium focus on frontline manager metrics with alerts and benchmarks. Kluster targets mid-market pipeline analytics. Coefficient pulls CRM data into Google Sheets for custom analysis. Choose the tool that serves your primary analytics audience.\n\nData quality constrains every analytics tool. Dashboards showing pipeline velocity are meaningless if reps don't update deal stages promptly. Activity metrics are wrong if reps make calls outside the tracked system. Conversion rates are skewed if deals sit in stale stages for weeks. Before investing in analytics tooling, ensure the underlying data is reliable. The best analytics tool built on unreliable data produces confident-looking dashboards with wrong numbers, which is worse than no dashboard at all.",
 "faqs": [
 {"question": "Do I need sales analytics software if I have Salesforce?", "answer": "Salesforce's native reporting covers basic metrics: pipeline by stage, activity counts, and standard dashboards. You need a separate analytics tool when you want cross-system data (combining CRM, email, call, and CS data), custom metric calculations Salesforce formulas can't express, or dashboard flexibility beyond what Salesforce Reports allow. For many teams, better Salesforce dashboard design is the right first step before buying another tool."},
 {"question": "What metrics should sales dashboards track?", "answer": "Core metrics include pipeline coverage ratio, stage-to-stage conversion rates, average deal cycle length, win rate by segment, rep activity volume, quota attainment by rep, and forecast accuracy over time. The specific metrics that matter depend on your sales motion. Outbound-heavy teams emphasize activity metrics. Enterprise teams focus on deal velocity and multi-threading. Recurring revenue businesses track expansion and churn alongside new business."},
 {"question": "How much does sales analytics software cost?", "answer": "Salesforce and HubSpot include native reporting in their platform pricing. Dedicated tools range from $30-$60/user/month (Atrium, Kluster) to $100+/user/month for enterprise platforms (Domo). Coefficient offers a spreadsheet-based approach starting around $50/month per connector. Pricing varies by data sources connected, number of dashboards, and user count. CRM-native reporting is included but limited. Dedicated tools cost more but deliver more flexibility."},
 {"question": "Can I build sales dashboards in Google Sheets or Excel?", "answer": "Yes, and tools like Coefficient make this practical by pulling live CRM data into Google Sheets. Spreadsheet dashboards work well for teams that want full control over metrics and formatting without learning a new platform. The trade-off is maintenance: formulas break, data connections time out, and scaling past a few dashboards requires significant effort. Dedicated tools handle the infrastructure so your team focuses on insights."},
 {"question": "What is the difference between sales analytics and revenue intelligence?", "answer": "Sales analytics reports on what happened: activity counts, conversion rates, pipeline snapshots. Revenue intelligence predicts what will happen: deal risk scoring, forecast modeling, engagement-based pipeline assessment. Analytics tools like Atrium and Kluster show you the data. Revenue intelligence tools like Clari and Aviso interpret the data and surface actionable recommendations. Most mature sales organizations use both."},
 ],
}
